{Cassiobury House}and its gardens were designed for the Earl of Essex in the 17th century.Some trees planted then are still alive.There are oak, beech and cedar nearly 300 years old. The variety of trees is a feature of the {Park}- all that now remains of the former estate.In July 1985 we found:-
cedar of Lebanon scarlet oak cypress Lawson cypress common oak poplar horse chestnut turkey oak willow sweet chestnut elderberry cherry Pissard plum grand fir beech copper beech sycamore larch London plane hornbeam ash rowan silver birch hawthorm lime yew
These plus the{R.Gade}and{Grand Union {Canal}make the{Park}a favourite 'country' area for the people of {Watford. }
